# ![]() welcome to the image-tutorial!
 
this tutorial explains how to implement and use images in slidenotes.io. 
 
to begin the presentation press `ctrl+enter` or the `play button`
---
## images in slidenotes: the image-tag

using images in presentations is quite common nowadays. although slidenotes are not meant to be heavily image based (sincerely there are better approaches to that kind of presentations) it is of course possible and easy to use images in slidenotes. 
 
images are represented in the slidenote-code with the image-tag you know from markdown: 
 
+++code
![imagedescription / alt-text](imagename)
+++
 
the text inside the square brackets **"[]"** will be interpreted as the **imagedescription or alt-text**, which will be displayed on devices where it's not possible to show the actual image itself—such as screenreaders or terminal-browsers. 
 
the imagename in the brackets **"()"** is the **name of the image** you want to use. this can be, but is not necessarily the same as the filename of the image you choose to use. in fact, it is up to you how you call your image. we will come back to that later. for now, let's continue with how you can implement your imagefiles to have something to work with ➡︎

---
## attaching an image file to a slidenote
 
while all your images are represented by image-tags in the code, the actual image-file must be attached to the slidenote-document.  
all attached image-files to a slidenote are stored (and encrypted!) together with the slidenote. in the image gallery you can get an overview over your image-files attached to this slidenote and if or where in the document it is used. 
 
to attach a image-file to a document you have not one, but two ways:
 
 
### 1. the image-selection-dialog
 
- click on the **image button** in the toolbar ![](toolbar.svg) to upload a new image or select one you already uploaded
- *or* type in the **image-tag** yourself
- *or* while your caret is insde one of your image-tags, open the image-selection-dialog via the **context-menu**
 
---
### 2. the image-gallery 
 
- open the image-gallery and attach a new image-file there 
in contrast to attaching your image via image-selection-dialog, this only attaches the image-file to the image-gallery—without using it yet. the newly attached image-file can later on be selected by connecting it to a image name via the image-selection-dialog. 
a click on the image in the image gallery will either enter a new image-tag on the current position of your caret or, in case the caret is inside an imagetag already, will change the imagename of the tag to the one selected from the image-gallery.   
 
---
## image-names and image-gallery

to connect your image-tag with the image-gallery, we make use of the image-names. this makes it convenient to re-use images in the document and replace them in one go if you decide to do so. 
so you could use the tag `![](my example image)` on several different slides in the document. if you changed your mind later on, you can replace the image the name uses by opening the image-selection-dialog and selecting (or uploading) another image. 
 
---
## images as background
 
images will be displayed as background-images of a slide or layout-block, whenever they are declared in the first line of the slide or block:
 
+++code
---
![](background 1)
 
## my first slide with background-image
 
---
![](background 2)
 
## this slide has a different background-image
 
---
![](background 1)
 
## this slide uses the same image as background as the first slide 
+++
---
+++code

 +++

+++

## positioning the images

the slidenote-editor makes use of how you position the image-tag inside your code. we use this concept to make it as easy to use as possible, without ever touching your mouse or defining complicated syntax-driven positioning of the image. you just write it down and the slidenoteeditor will take care of all the rest. 

###definitions of image-positioning

1. images **inside the line of a title** are positioned inside the title. they will be displayed in the height of the title, keeping its aspect-ratio. very useful for logo, for example
2. images **inside a textblock** will be displayed as icons inside the text, calculated by the height of the line of text
3. images at the **beginning of a block of text** will be interpreted as that they are on the left side, the following text will float around the image 
4. images at the **end of a block of text** will be interpreted as they are on the right side of the textblock and the text will float around the image   
5. images, which are the **sole content of the slide**, but not in the first line of the slide, will be displayed as big as possible, centered on the slide
 
---
## imagedescriptions and image-subtitles

images can have *descriptions or alt-text*, which will be displayed whenever or wherever the browser doesn't want to display the image. and it is read by screenreaders. 
giving your image an alt-text is a good way to keep your content more accessible and is highly recommended. the alt-text is **not bound to the image-name**. you can use different alt-texts in several image-tags if you want to. 
also you can give your images some subtitles: 
if an image-tag is the sole element of a line and in the following line comes a line with text, the text is used as subtitle and will be displayed directly under the image: 
+++layout:inline
![image of a dog](example)
this is lapa, a friendly dog
 
+++code
---
## a slide to demonstrate images with subtitles
 
![an example image](example)
subtitle to the image
 
some more text, following, disconnected with the image
+++
 
+++
 
---
## quality of images

because all images are attached to the document directly, the size of the image-files used in the document reflects the size of the document in general. 
when they are encrypted, the size becomes bigger. 
therefore it is good practice to think about the quality you use when attaching a image-file to the slidenote by loading it in the image-gallery. 
 
but don't worry, you don't have to open a different app to alter the image-size. we've built the posibility to choose the quality into the process of adding the image to the image-gallery. 
you can choose between three different options: **small, medium** and **large** and the slidenote editor will take care of resizing the image to the desired quality. keep in mind that in this process the image will be changed to a *.png-image*. if you want to add a .gif-animation, the animation would not be used at all. in that case you should use the option "**original"**.
